  "verdict_tag": "PHYSICAL-FRONTIER",
  "verdict": "frac_B~O(10%) requires R\u0302\u22480.57 (range 0.13\u20130.75), i.e. BELOW the discreteness scale (R\u0302<1: curvature radius < mean spacing \u2248 Planck length under the stated assumption). This is a PHYSICAL frontier, not merely technical: the mechanism needs near-/sub-Planckian curvature, so the observable universe (R\u0302 astronomically large) gets only the flat tail (~0) -- this framework does NOT explain why the observable universe has photons. NOT the hard structural death (R\u0302\u226a0.1): the value sits at the 0.5 boundary, so running E6e at R\u0302=1.5,1.0,0.5 to CONFIRM the \u221d1/R\u0302\u00b2 law within the valid continuum regime is defensible, but it would confirm a Planck-scale requirement, not bring the photon within reach. (NB: the exponential-in-R\u0302 model, R\u00b2\u22480.99 on the excess, SATURATES below 0.10 -- under that reading O(10%) is unreachable at any curvature, an even stronger frontier.)"
